  "prompt": "What is the difference between fibromyalgia and rheumatoid arthritis?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between fibromyalgia and rheumatoid arthritis (RA):\n\nFibromyalgia:\n1. Causes widespread muscle pain and tenderness\n2. Not an inflammatory condition\n3. Does not cause joint damage\n4. Associated with fatigue, sleep problems, and mood issues\n5. Diagnosed through symptom evaluation and ruling out other conditions\n6. Primarily treated with pain management and lifestyle changes\n\nRheumatoid Arthritis:\n1. Autoimmune disease that causes joint inflammation\n2. Causes joint swelling, stiffness, and potential joint destruction\n3. Can lead to permanent joint damage and deformity\n4. Typically affects joints symmetrically (both sides of the body)\n5. Diagnosed through blood tests, x-rays, and physical examination\n6. Treated with disease-modifying drugs, anti-inflammatory medications, and immunosuppressants\n\nSimilarities:\n- Both can cause chronic pain\n- Both can impact quality of life\n- Both can benefit from exercise and stress management\n- Both are more common in women\n\nWhile they have different mechanisms and treatments, both conditions require medical management and can significantly affect a person's daily functioning.",
